						<summary>

						

						<p>Pillar in the Sāhebu Bazaar.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Śaka 1091: 1169 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription is dated in Śaka 1091 which is said to correspond to 1169 A.D.</p>						

						<p>It records a gift of 55 sheep left in the hands of a shepherd Navedana, son of Kalle-bōya, for burning a perpetual lamp in the temple of Trikōṭīśvaradēva on the day of <hi rend="italic">Uttarāyaṇa-saṅkrānti,</hi> for the merit of his parents. The shepherd undertook to supply a <hi rend="italic">māna</hi> of ghee daily to maintain the above endowment.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. X, No. 169.</p>						

						</summary>
